WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.470 align:middle line:84%
[SQUEAKING] [CLICKING]
[RUSTLING] [CLICKING]

00:00:07.470 --> 00:00:10.470 align:middle line:90%


00:00:10.470 --> 00:00:13.380 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Let us start.

00:00:13.380 --> 00:00:18.530 align:middle line:84%
So last time, we started talking
about the following process.

00:00:18.530 --> 00:00:21.380 align:middle line:90%


00:00:21.380 --> 00:00:30.900 align:middle line:90%
So you consider e plus e minus--

00:00:30.900 --> 00:00:35.190 align:middle line:84%
so the electron, the positron
they scatter and then they

00:00:35.190 --> 00:00:40.110 align:middle line:84%
will annihilate and that
creates some other particles.

00:00:40.110 --> 00:00:40.890 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:00:40.890 --> 00:00:44.460 align:middle line:84%
So b and the b bar--
some final particles

00:00:44.460 --> 00:00:47.830 align:middle line:84%
can be different
kinds of things.

00:00:47.830 --> 00:00:49.500 align:middle line:84%
So if we draw the
Feynman diagram

00:00:49.500 --> 00:00:54.285 align:middle line:84%
with the time going up,
and then the process

00:00:54.285 --> 00:00:55.410 align:middle line:90%
will be like the following.

00:00:55.410 --> 00:00:59.760 align:middle line:90%


00:00:59.760 --> 00:01:02.020 align:middle line:90%
So the initial particle--

00:01:02.020 --> 00:01:05.700 align:middle line:84%
so this is the e minus
and this is e plus.

00:01:05.700 --> 00:01:11.650 align:middle line:84%
And then we have b
and the b bar, OK?

00:01:11.650 --> 00:01:14.090 align:middle line:90%
So we can--

00:01:14.090 --> 00:01:15.260 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:01:15.260 --> 00:01:20.900 align:middle line:84%
So such a process is a very
important discovery machine

00:01:20.900 --> 00:01:24.530 align:middle line:90%
for new particles, OK?

00:01:24.530 --> 00:01:40.690 align:middle line:84%
Very important for
discovering new particles.

00:01:40.690 --> 00:01:44.180 align:middle line:84%
So let me just mention
two examples here.

00:01:44.180 --> 00:01:51.310 align:middle line:90%
So in 1974 to 1976 at SLAC--

00:01:51.310 --> 00:01:55.900 align:middle line:84%
so SLAC is called Stanford
Linear Acceleration Center.

00:01:55.900 --> 00:02:00.580 align:middle line:84%
So they have an electron
positron collider.

00:02:00.580 --> 00:02:05.440 align:middle line:84%
And so there they first
discovered the tau particle.

00:02:05.440 --> 00:02:10.370 align:middle line:90%


00:02:10.370 --> 00:02:12.530 align:middle line:90%
And this tau particle--

00:02:12.530 --> 00:02:15.710 align:middle line:90%
it's mass is the 1.8 GeV.

00:02:15.710 --> 00:02:27.200 align:middle line:84%
So when your total energy is
greater than twice the 1.8 GeV,

00:02:27.200 --> 00:02:31.100 align:middle line:84%
then you can, in principle,
pair create this tau part--

00:02:31.100 --> 00:02:34.070 align:middle line:90%
tau plus and tau minus.

00:02:34.070 --> 00:02:42.710 align:middle line:84%
And another example is in
1974, again, at the SLAC.

00:02:42.710 --> 00:02:48.080 align:middle line:84%
And the e plus, e
minus goes to c, c bar.

00:02:48.080 --> 00:02:50.750 align:middle line:90%
So c is the charm quark here.

00:02:50.750 --> 00:02:52.590 align:middle line:90%
OK, it's the charm quark here.

00:02:52.590 --> 00:02:57.515 align:middle line:84%
So what they observed is
the bound state of the c,

00:02:57.515 --> 00:03:00.240 align:middle line:90%
c bar-- call it J/psi.

00:03:00.240 --> 00:03:03.630 align:middle line:84%
So under the mass of the
J/psi, it's about 3.1 GeV.

00:03:03.630 --> 00:03:06.430 align:middle line:90%


00:03:06.430 --> 00:03:09.180 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:03:09.180 --> 00:03:11.790 align:middle line:90%
3.1 GeV.

00:03:11.790 --> 00:03:18.850 align:middle line:84%
So this J/psi-- so this particle
was discovered at the same time

00:03:18.850 --> 00:03:23.710 align:middle line:84%
at Brookhaven
through the proton--

00:03:23.710 --> 00:03:28.100 align:middle line:84%
through the collision of the
protons by our own colleague

00:03:28.100 --> 00:03:29.350 align:middle line:90%
Samuel Ting.

00:03:29.350 --> 00:03:34.540 align:middle line:84%
And then they both get the
Nobel Prize in 1975, I think.

00:03:34.540 --> 00:03:35.350 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:03:35.350 --> 00:03:39.610 align:middle line:84%
So there was actually
a funny story regarding

00:03:39.610 --> 00:03:41.870 align:middle line:90%
the discovery of this particle.

00:03:41.870 --> 00:03:48.820 align:middle line:84%
So at Brookhaven, they
collide the protons

00:03:48.820 --> 00:03:51.160 align:middle line:90%
on the fixed target.

00:03:51.160 --> 00:03:54.160 align:middle line:84%
So that is a much
messier machine,

00:03:54.160 --> 00:03:58.240 align:middle line:84%
because protons contain
lots of quarks and gluons

00:03:58.240 --> 00:04:05.080 align:middle line:84%
and so it's with
strong interactions.

00:04:05.080 --> 00:04:09.400 align:middle line:84%
So if you collide
high enough energy,

00:04:09.400 --> 00:04:13.120 align:middle line:90%
you can create any particles.

00:04:13.120 --> 00:04:15.190 align:middle line:84%
But since it's involving
strong interactions,

00:04:15.190 --> 00:04:17.510 align:middle line:84%
and strong interactions
have many, many particles.

00:04:17.510 --> 00:04:21.840 align:middle line:84%
So the so the collider at
Brookhaven is very, very messy.

00:04:21.840 --> 00:04:22.340 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:22.340 --> 00:04:23.930 align:middle line:84%
So in order to find
the new particles,

00:04:23.930 --> 00:04:25.560 align:middle line:90%
it's very, very difficult.

00:04:25.560 --> 00:04:26.060 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:26.060 --> 00:04:31.940 align:middle line:84%
But they managed to find this
new particle at Brookhaven.

00:04:31.940 --> 00:04:38.180 align:middle line:84%
But Samuel Ting was famously
extraordinarily meticulous.

00:04:38.180 --> 00:04:41.600 align:middle line:84%
OK, so he wanted to
be absolutely right,

00:04:41.600 --> 00:04:44.050 align:middle line:90%
so he was checking and checking.

00:04:44.050 --> 00:04:45.670 align:middle line:90%
So during one of the--

00:04:45.670 --> 00:04:48.730 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, so this is a rumor.

00:04:48.730 --> 00:04:52.870 align:middle line:84%
So the rumor said that during
one of the checking process--

00:04:52.870 --> 00:04:57.220 align:middle line:84%
and somehow the
rumor spread that he

00:04:57.220 --> 00:04:59.770 align:middle line:90%
discovered a new particle.

00:04:59.770 --> 00:05:02.650 align:middle line:84%
And so the person was doing
the experiment at SLAC

00:05:02.650 --> 00:05:04.690 align:middle line:90%
and called him up.

00:05:04.690 --> 00:05:07.180 align:middle line:84%
Even the rumor--
the rumor even--

00:05:07.180 --> 00:05:10.150 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, so the news leaked.

00:05:10.150 --> 00:05:14.350 align:middle line:84%
It even leaked the energy scale
of the particle they found.

00:05:14.350 --> 00:05:16.690 align:middle line:84%
And then the person
was doing the register

00:05:16.690 --> 00:05:20.200 align:middle line:84%
at the SLAC then
called the Samuel Ting.

00:05:20.200 --> 00:05:25.080 align:middle line:84%
He said, oh, I heard you
have found a new particle.

00:05:25.080 --> 00:05:27.590 align:middle line:90%
Samuel Ting said, no, I didn't.

00:05:27.590 --> 00:05:28.770 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:05:28.770 --> 00:05:32.650 align:middle line:90%
He didn't want to have the--

00:05:32.650 --> 00:05:35.080 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, actually it's not very
good, because I'm recorded.

00:05:35.080 --> 00:05:38.050 align:middle line:90%


00:05:38.050 --> 00:05:39.280 align:middle line:90%
I'm recorded.

00:05:39.280 --> 00:05:44.920 align:middle line:84%
So I think this maybe it's
not a good spread rumors.

00:05:44.920 --> 00:05:49.120 align:middle line:84%
If it's not recorded,
actually, I can tell the story.

00:05:49.120 --> 00:05:50.590 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:05:50.590 --> 00:05:59.020 align:middle line:84%
Anyway so accordingly,
then the register

00:05:59.020 --> 00:06:01.360 align:middle line:84%
said then, oh, you
didn't find the particle.

00:06:01.360 --> 00:06:03.010 align:middle line:90%
Then I can discover it.

00:06:03.010 --> 00:06:05.350 align:middle line:84%
Because they already
knew the energy scale.

00:06:05.350 --> 00:06:07.930 align:middle line:84%
They already had
the energy scale.

00:06:07.930 --> 00:06:10.480 align:middle line:84%
And this is a very,
very clean machine.

00:06:10.480 --> 00:06:14.120 align:middle line:84%
So electron, positron, when they
collide only energy created.

00:06:14.120 --> 00:06:15.820 align:middle line:84%
So it don't create
a lot of junks.

00:06:15.820 --> 00:06:18.250 align:middle line:84%
And if you add the right
energy, you can immediately

00:06:18.250 --> 00:06:19.720 align:middle line:90%
find the new particle.

00:06:19.720 --> 00:06:21.350 align:middle line:90%
You don't need to do much work.

00:06:21.350 --> 00:06:25.240 align:middle line:84%
And so they put the machine
at that energy, immediately,

00:06:25.240 --> 00:06:27.520 align:middle line:90%
the new particle was discovered.

00:06:27.520 --> 00:06:29.830 align:middle line:90%
And so they were--

00:06:29.830 --> 00:06:30.430 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:06:30.430 --> 00:06:35.360 align:middle line:84%
So they were awarded
the Nobel Prize jointly.

00:06:35.360 --> 00:06:36.170 align:middle line:90%
Anyway.

00:06:36.170 --> 00:06:40.610 align:middle line:84%
So this was an
important discovery,

00:06:40.610 --> 00:06:45.420 align:middle line:84%
because before that, people
didn't believe quarks exist,

00:06:45.420 --> 00:06:47.630 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:06:47.630 --> 00:06:49.250 align:middle line:84%
People didn't quite
believe the quark

00:06:49.250 --> 00:06:53.850 align:middle line:84%
existed, even though there
are many models, et cetera.

00:06:53.850 --> 00:06:56.300 align:middle line:84%
And there are lots
of other evidences.

00:06:56.300 --> 00:07:01.760 align:middle line:90%
But this was the first--

00:07:01.760 --> 00:07:06.230 align:middle line:84%
yeah, because C-quark
is very heavy.

00:07:06.230 --> 00:07:09.960 align:middle line:84%
And so c and c bar, they
bound not very strongly.

00:07:09.960 --> 00:07:12.740 align:middle line:84%
And so this is the
first direct evidence

00:07:12.740 --> 00:07:14.340 align:middle line:90%
actually quark existed.

00:07:14.340 --> 00:07:16.830 align:middle line:84%
And so this actually
shocked the community.

00:07:16.830 --> 00:07:19.410 align:middle line:84%
So this was
discovered in October.

00:07:19.410 --> 00:07:21.320 align:middle line:84%
So they call it the
October Revolution.

00:07:21.320 --> 00:07:24.260 align:middle line:90%


00:07:24.260 --> 00:07:29.930 align:middle line:84%
So yeah, it played a very
important role for people

00:07:29.930 --> 00:07:33.040 align:middle line:84%
to accept the
existence of quarks.

00:07:33.040 --> 00:07:33.880 align:middle line:90%
Anyway.

00:07:33.880 --> 00:07:40.890 align:middle line:84%
So in particular, by looking
at the more general process--

00:07:40.890 --> 00:07:44.480 align:middle line:90%
so this goes to hadrons.

00:07:44.480 --> 00:07:45.960 align:middle line:90%
OK, you just collide them.

00:07:45.960 --> 00:07:47.000 align:middle line:90%
And then you look at it.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:47.960 align:middle line:90%
It's going to hadrons.

00:07:47.960 --> 00:07:57.190 align:middle line:84%
You can actually show that
the quarks have three colors.

00:07:57.190 --> 00:08:06.050 align:middle line:90%


00:08:06.050 --> 00:08:06.620 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:08:06.620 --> 00:08:10.290 align:middle line:84%
You can show quark
have three colors.

00:08:10.290 --> 00:08:14.650 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, so we
will see that, OK?

00:08:14.650 --> 00:08:20.330 align:middle line:84%
So before doing that, let's
first have to do a calculation,

00:08:20.330 --> 00:08:20.830 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:08:20.830 --> 00:08:24.350 align:middle line:84%
So we have to calculate
this explicitly.

00:08:24.350 --> 00:08:24.850 align:middle line:90%
Let me see.

00:08:24.850 --> 00:08:26.440 align:middle line:90%
I get my page a little bit.

00:08:26.440 --> 00:08:31.980 align:middle line:90%


00:08:31.980 --> 00:08:32.710 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:08:32.710 --> 00:08:33.210 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:08:33.210 --> 00:08:35.370 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so first we have
to do a calculation.

00:08:35.370 --> 00:08:37.740 align:middle line:84%
We have to calculate
this process, OK?

00:08:37.740 --> 00:08:40.500 align:middle line:84%
So after we have
calculated this,

00:08:40.500 --> 00:08:45.270 align:middle line:84%
then it's obvious how
this can tell us why

00:08:45.270 --> 00:08:46.740 align:middle line:90%
the quark have three colors.

00:08:46.740 --> 00:08:47.430 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:08:47.430 --> 00:08:48.150 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:08:48.150 --> 00:08:50.733 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So since you only see
the bound state of the quarks,

00:08:50.733 --> 00:08:54.950 align:middle line:84%
how can you know for sure
that they are a bound state?

00:08:54.950 --> 00:08:57.300 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah, so indeed.

00:08:57.300 --> 00:09:00.140 align:middle line:84%
So that's why, for
many years, if you

00:09:00.140 --> 00:09:02.450 align:middle line:84%
look at the proton,
neutron, and the pion,

00:09:02.450 --> 00:09:04.260 align:middle line:90%
they're very tightly bound.

00:09:04.260 --> 00:09:07.990 align:middle line:84%
And so even though
there were models

00:09:07.990 --> 00:09:10.240 align:middle line:90%
about the quarks inside there--

00:09:10.240 --> 00:09:13.150 align:middle line:90%
so it's not quite--

00:09:13.150 --> 00:09:16.690 align:middle line:84%
yeah, but in the c
case, c are very heavy.

00:09:16.690 --> 00:09:20.380 align:middle line:84%
And so they form a
weakly bound state.

00:09:20.380 --> 00:09:23.110 align:middle line:84%
And so in the sense that
you're looking at the--

00:09:23.110 --> 00:09:26.380 align:middle line:90%
yeah, so here, it's--

00:09:26.380 --> 00:09:28.960 align:middle line:84%
in a sense, you can
look at the C-quark,

00:09:28.960 --> 00:09:32.104 align:middle line:84%
because it's a very weakly bound
state of the c and C-quark.

00:09:32.104 --> 00:09:34.920 align:middle line:90%


00:09:34.920 --> 00:09:35.610 align:middle line:90%
Other questions?

00:09:35.610 --> 00:09:36.600 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:09:36.600 --> 00:09:40.240 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Does weakly bound
imply it's usually larger?

00:09:40.240 --> 00:09:41.890 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:09:41.890 --> 00:09:45.130 align:middle line:84%
Weakly bound just say
you can probe with the--

00:09:45.130 --> 00:09:47.110 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, you can essentially--

00:09:47.110 --> 00:09:49.720 align:middle line:84%
you can probe the internal
structure much easier.

00:09:49.720 --> 00:09:55.666 align:middle line:90%


00:09:55.666 --> 00:09:59.890 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: If electron collider
is much cleaner than Hadron

00:09:59.890 --> 00:10:03.670 align:middle line:84%
Collider, then why is like the
most important machine right

00:10:03.670 --> 00:10:05.440 align:middle line:90%
now is the Hadron Collider?

00:10:05.440 --> 00:10:06.700 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:10:06.700 --> 00:10:11.890 align:middle line:84%
That's good, because electron
collider is more difficult,

00:10:11.890 --> 00:10:14.540 align:middle line:84%
because you have to
build a straight line,

00:10:14.540 --> 00:10:19.000 align:middle line:84%
and because the electron have
a much stronger synchrotron

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:22.400 align:middle line:84%
radiation if they're
moving in the circle.

00:10:22.400 --> 00:10:25.010 align:middle line:84%
And so that loses
a lot of energy.

00:10:25.010 --> 00:10:26.802 align:middle line:84%
And so that's the
electron collider.

00:10:26.802 --> 00:10:28.510 align:middle line:84%
They should build a
strong straight line.

00:10:28.510 --> 00:10:31.120 align:middle line:84%
But straight line you cannot
have very high energy,

00:10:31.120 --> 00:10:33.050 align:middle line:90%
require very long distance.

00:10:33.050 --> 00:10:36.550 align:middle line:84%
And so that's why
a lot of people

00:10:36.550 --> 00:10:40.750 align:middle line:84%
built the proton
collider, which is easier.

00:10:40.750 --> 00:10:44.470 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, it's easier
to get higher energy.

00:10:44.470 --> 00:10:49.330 align:middle line:84%
But the next generation of the
accelerator of the LHC, people

00:10:49.330 --> 00:10:53.210 align:middle line:84%
are talking about building
an electron collider again.

00:10:53.210 --> 00:10:53.710 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:10:53.710 --> 00:10:56.240 align:middle line:90%


00:10:56.240 --> 00:10:57.020 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:10:57.020 --> 00:10:59.210 align:middle line:84%
So now let's try
to calculate this.

00:10:59.210 --> 00:11:00.140 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:11:00.140 --> 00:11:03.920 align:middle line:84%
So essentially we need to
calculate this diagram.

00:11:03.920 --> 00:11:06.180 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, this
diagram is very easy.

00:11:06.180 --> 00:11:09.350 align:middle line:84%
We need to calculate the cross
section corresponding to this.

00:11:09.350 --> 00:11:13.710 align:middle line:90%
So let me just label a label.

00:11:13.710 --> 00:11:15.230 align:middle line:90%
So this is e minus.

00:11:15.230 --> 00:11:17.030 align:middle line:90%
So this is e plus.

00:11:17.030 --> 00:11:18.020 align:middle line:90%
So this would be b.

00:11:18.020 --> 00:11:20.490 align:middle line:90%
And this will be b bar.

00:11:20.490 --> 00:11:22.200 align:middle line:90%
So let me label the momentum.

00:11:22.200 --> 00:11:25.700 align:middle line:90%
So here, let's take p1, r1.

00:11:25.700 --> 00:11:32.400 align:middle line:84%
And then this would
be p2, r2 bar.

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:35.250 align:middle line:84%
So tell you this
is an antiparticle.

00:11:35.250 --> 00:11:39.950 align:middle line:90%
And so this one is k1, s1.

00:11:39.950 --> 00:11:45.020 align:middle line:90%
And this one is k2 s2 bar.

00:11:45.020 --> 00:11:46.250 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:11:46.250 --> 00:11:51.160 align:middle line:84%
And so the amplitude for
this will be M. So the cross

00:11:51.160 --> 00:11:53.610 align:middle line:90%
section.

00:11:53.610 --> 00:11:59.130 align:middle line:84%
So now, suppose we consider
unpolarized process.

00:11:59.130 --> 00:12:02.315 align:middle line:84%
As we discussed last
time, the cross section --

00:12:02.315 --> 00:12:06.130 align:middle line:90%


00:12:06.130 --> 00:12:13.850 align:middle line:84%
yeah, so d sigma, d omega should
be proportional to the spin.

00:12:13.850 --> 00:12:19.090 align:middle line:84%
So we should sum over
all the final states--

00:12:19.090 --> 00:12:21.370 align:middle line:84%
sum over the polarization
of the final states,

00:12:21.370 --> 00:12:23.860 align:middle line:84%
because we don't measure
individual polarization.

00:12:23.860 --> 00:12:28.060 align:middle line:84%
But we also should average
over the polarization

00:12:28.060 --> 00:12:30.730 align:middle line:90%
of the initial states.

00:12:30.730 --> 00:12:34.660 align:middle line:84%
So the result, as we discussed
at the end of last lecture,

00:12:34.660 --> 00:12:37.060 align:middle line:84%
is that you need to
take one quarter, come

00:12:37.060 --> 00:12:43.330 align:middle line:84%
from the average over the spin
of these two initial particles,

00:12:43.330 --> 00:12:48.190 align:middle line:84%
and then, just sum of spins
of all the particles, OK?

00:12:48.190 --> 00:12:56.890 align:middle line:90%


00:12:56.890 --> 00:12:57.490 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:12:57.490 --> 00:13:02.610 align:middle line:90%
And right.

00:13:02.610 --> 00:13:04.290 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:13:04.290 --> 00:13:06.510 align:middle line:84%
So that's the thing we
need to-- so let's just

00:13:06.510 --> 00:13:08.860 align:middle line:90%
try to first compute the m.

00:13:08.860 --> 00:13:14.910 align:middle line:90%
So m is given by--

00:13:14.910 --> 00:13:17.420 align:middle line:90%
OK, so we just follow our rule.

00:13:17.420 --> 00:13:21.620 align:middle line:84%
So you follow the
fermionic line, OK?

00:13:21.620 --> 00:13:24.240 align:middle line:90%
So here there's a vertex.

00:13:24.240 --> 00:13:26.570 align:middle line:90%
So here there's a gamma.

00:13:26.570 --> 00:13:32.690 align:middle line:84%
So each vertex gives
you minus ie gamma mu.

00:13:32.690 --> 00:13:33.500 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:13:33.500 --> 00:13:36.890 align:middle line:84%
So if you follow
this one, then we

00:13:36.890 --> 00:13:52.830 align:middle line:84%
get v bar r2, p2, minus
ie gamma mu and ur1 p1.

00:13:52.830 --> 00:13:54.050 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:13:54.050 --> 00:13:58.450 align:middle line:84%
So this is coming from
this fermionic line.

00:13:58.450 --> 00:14:02.840 align:middle line:84%
And from this fermionic
line, we start from here.

00:14:02.840 --> 00:14:07.160 align:middle line:90%
So this would be the u.

00:14:07.160 --> 00:14:07.880 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:14:07.880 --> 00:14:09.740 align:middle line:90%
Also, we have this propagator.

00:14:09.740 --> 00:14:14.420 align:middle line:84%
Let me just write down the
propagator for the photon.

00:14:14.420 --> 00:14:16.490 align:middle line:84%
So let's take xi
equal to 1 gauge.

00:14:16.490 --> 00:14:19.580 align:middle line:90%


00:14:19.580 --> 00:14:24.220 align:middle line:84%
The Lorentz gauge
with xi equal to 1.

00:14:24.220 --> 00:14:25.640 align:middle line:90%
And then, lets follow this line.

00:14:25.640 --> 00:14:29.620 align:middle line:84%
So here, we should
have a vertex gamma nu.

00:14:29.620 --> 00:14:30.160 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:14:30.160 --> 00:14:50.930 align:middle line:84%
And then we will have u bar s1
k1 minus ie gamma nu v s2 k2.

00:14:50.930 --> 00:14:51.800 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:14:51.800 --> 00:14:55.090 align:middle line:90%
So this is the full amplitude.

00:14:55.090 --> 00:14:59.900 align:middle line:90%
So this is a number.

00:14:59.900 --> 00:15:04.570 align:middle line:84%
OK, so this is a number,
because this is a row vector.

00:15:04.570 --> 00:15:05.860 align:middle line:90%
This is a matrix.

00:15:05.860 --> 00:15:09.220 align:middle line:84%
And this is a column vector,
so this will be a number.

00:15:09.220 --> 00:15:11.470 align:middle line:84%
And similarly, this
will be a number.

00:15:11.470 --> 00:15:15.417 align:middle line:84%
And then the mu nu indices are
contracted with the propagator

00:15:15.417 --> 00:15:16.000 align:middle line:90%
of the photon.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:19.790 align:middle line:90%


00:15:19.790 --> 00:15:23.060 align:middle line:84%
So actually, if I
want to be precise,

00:15:23.060 --> 00:15:26.090 align:middle line:84%
there's actually a
factor of i here.

00:15:26.090 --> 00:15:29.550 align:middle line:84%
But this factor of i is
not important, because--

00:15:29.550 --> 00:15:31.950 align:middle line:90%
and then the q--

00:15:31.950 --> 00:15:35.210 align:middle line:84%
so the q is the momentum
of the photon here.

00:15:35.210 --> 00:15:38.630 align:middle line:84%
So the q should be the sum
of the initial momentum.

00:15:38.630 --> 00:15:46.630 align:middle line:84%
OK, so q should be
equal to p1 plus p2.

00:15:46.630 --> 00:15:53.830 align:middle line:84%
And also this means that the q
square is equal to minus s, OK?

00:15:53.830 --> 00:16:00.180 align:middle line:84%
Remember s is defined to be the
minus p1 plus p2 square, OK?

00:16:00.180 --> 00:16:05.580 align:middle line:84%
So now we can write this
amplitude using a shorthand

00:16:05.580 --> 00:16:08.220 align:middle line:90%
notation.

00:16:08.220 --> 00:16:10.740 align:middle line:84%
So if I forget all this
momentum dependence,

00:16:10.740 --> 00:16:18.150 align:middle line:84%
and then this is equal to minus
ie square divided by s, OK?

00:16:18.150 --> 00:16:22.170 align:middle line:84%
If you cancel all the i's,
and then we have two terms--

00:16:22.170 --> 00:16:36.485 align:middle line:84%
v bar r2 gamma nu and ur1 and
the u bar s1 gamma nu vs2.

00:16:36.485 --> 00:16:41.910 align:middle line:90%


00:16:41.910 --> 00:16:45.520 align:middle line:90%
And now we need to--

00:16:45.520 --> 00:16:49.690 align:middle line:84%
then what we need to do is we
need to square it and sum over

00:16:49.690 --> 00:16:51.310 align:middle line:90%
all the spin.

00:16:51.310 --> 00:16:54.790 align:middle line:84%
And then we plug the
resulting expression

00:16:54.790 --> 00:16:57.940 align:middle line:84%
into the formula we derived
for the cross section

00:16:57.940 --> 00:17:00.280 align:middle line:90%
we derived last time, OK?

00:17:00.280 --> 00:17:02.890 align:middle line:90%


00:17:02.890 --> 00:17:07.329 align:middle line:84%
So the whole calculation
is a little bit tedious.

00:17:07.329 --> 00:17:08.980 align:middle line:84%
But I think we
should at least go

00:17:08.980 --> 00:17:11.500 align:middle line:84%
through one such
calculation, because this

00:17:11.500 --> 00:17:19.839 align:middle line:84%
is the kind of prime
example of QED calculation.

00:17:19.839 --> 00:17:25.569 align:middle line:84%
So each of us should at least
see once in our life, OK?

00:17:25.569 --> 00:17:27.535 align:middle line:84%
So we will do it
explicitly here.

00:17:27.535 --> 00:17:30.700 align:middle line:90%


00:17:30.700 --> 00:17:32.920 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: The final
line needs metric.

00:17:32.920 --> 00:17:34.570 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: The final
line is a metric.

00:17:34.570 --> 00:17:36.700 align:middle line:84%
You are right,
but I can do that,

00:17:36.700 --> 00:17:38.290 align:middle line:90%
just put the gamma mu here.

00:17:38.290 --> 00:17:41.460 align:middle line:90%


00:17:41.460 --> 00:17:45.000 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Do we to
keep the i epsilon?

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:45.960 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Oh, OK.

00:17:45.960 --> 00:17:50.490 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, also here, because the
q square is never equal to 0,

00:17:50.490 --> 00:17:52.370 align:middle line:84%
so we don't need to
care about i epsilon.

00:17:52.370 --> 00:17:55.450 align:middle line:90%


00:17:55.450 --> 00:17:56.690 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:17:56.690 --> 00:17:57.890 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:17:57.890 --> 00:17:59.215 align:middle line:90%
So now let's do the square.

00:17:59.215 --> 00:18:01.735 align:middle line:90%


00:18:01.735 --> 00:18:02.735 align:middle line:90%
Now let's to the square.

00:18:02.735 --> 00:18:05.390 align:middle line:90%


00:18:05.390 --> 00:18:09.790 align:middle line:84%
So square-- we just square this
term and square this term, OK?

00:18:09.790 --> 00:18:11.365 align:middle line:90%
So when we square this term--

00:18:11.365 --> 00:18:15.650 align:middle line:90%


00:18:15.650 --> 00:18:17.230 align:middle line:90%
so we also square this term.

00:18:17.230 --> 00:18:20.220 align:middle line:84%
So here, we just get the e
to the power 4 divided by s

00:18:20.220 --> 00:18:21.910 align:middle line:90%
square.

00:18:21.910 --> 00:18:27.300 align:middle line:84%
And when we square this
term, we just get another--

00:18:27.300 --> 00:18:31.270 align:middle line:84%
yeah, so this is
gamma nu gamma mu.

00:18:31.270 --> 00:18:36.720 align:middle line:84%
So if we square it, then
we get another term.

00:18:36.720 --> 00:18:38.085 align:middle line:90%
So we just copy this term.

00:18:38.085 --> 00:18:41.530 align:middle line:90%


00:18:41.530 --> 00:18:42.790 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, let me just copy here.

00:18:42.790 --> 00:18:50.300 align:middle line:90%


00:18:50.300 --> 00:18:56.930 align:middle line:84%
ur1-- Yeah, when we square it,
we get another copy of this.

00:18:56.930 --> 00:18:59.260 align:middle line:90%
And so let me just write it.

00:18:59.260 --> 00:19:02.020 align:middle line:90%


00:19:02.020 --> 00:19:04.870 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, sorry.

00:19:04.870 --> 00:19:07.390 align:middle line:84%
So we take the
complex conjugate.

00:19:07.390 --> 00:19:10.180 align:middle line:84%
So when we take the complex,
we need to take the modulus.

00:19:10.180 --> 00:19:12.650 align:middle line:84%
So that means we need
to multiply this,

00:19:12.650 --> 00:19:15.130 align:middle line:90%
with its own complex conjugate.

00:19:15.130 --> 00:19:18.760 align:middle line:84%
And the complex
conjugate of this

00:19:18.760 --> 00:19:29.290 align:middle line:84%
is given by u bar r1,
then gamma nu and vr2,

00:19:29.290 --> 00:19:35.820 align:middle line:84%
and then, times this one
and its complex conjugate.

00:19:35.820 --> 00:19:52.390 align:middle line:84%
And so we have us1 bar gamma nu
vs2 and vs2 bar gamma nu us1.

00:19:52.390 --> 00:19:53.100 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:19:53.100 --> 00:19:59.160 align:middle line:84%
So this is the original
copy with the nu contract

00:19:59.160 --> 00:20:00.450 align:middle line:90%
with this nu.

00:20:00.450 --> 00:20:03.480 align:middle line:84%
And this is the complex
conjugate with this nu contract

00:20:03.480 --> 00:20:04.455 align:middle line:90%
with this nu, OK?

00:20:04.455 --> 00:20:12.710 align:middle line:90%


00:20:12.710 --> 00:20:13.210 align:middle line:90%
Good?

00:20:13.210 --> 00:20:16.530 align:middle line:90%


00:20:16.530 --> 00:20:20.180 align:middle line:90%
So this looks like a mess.

00:20:20.180 --> 00:20:23.830 align:middle line:90%
OK, this look like a big mess.

00:20:23.830 --> 00:20:25.870 align:middle line:84%
And it turns out
actually, there's

00:20:25.870 --> 00:20:29.080 align:middle line:84%
a series of beautiful
tricks we can use

00:20:29.080 --> 00:20:31.240 align:middle line:90%
to calculate this quantity, OK?

00:20:31.240 --> 00:20:35.350 align:middle line:84%
So naively, you say, oh
to calculate this thing,

00:20:35.350 --> 00:20:38.020 align:middle line:84%
I have to plug-in
the individual wave

00:20:38.020 --> 00:20:43.480 align:middle line:84%
functions for this v and u, et
cetera we worked out before.

00:20:43.480 --> 00:20:46.120 align:middle line:84%
But fortunately, actually,
we don't need to do it, OK?

00:20:46.120 --> 00:20:49.780 align:middle line:84%
So we can actually go
through a series of tricks.

00:20:49.780 --> 00:20:51.860 align:middle line:90%
And then we don't have to do it.

00:20:51.860 --> 00:20:52.945 align:middle line:90%
So the first trick--

00:20:52.945 --> 00:20:55.610 align:middle line:90%


00:20:55.610 --> 00:20:59.920 align:middle line:90%
you say this is a number, OK?

00:20:59.920 --> 00:21:07.260 align:middle line:84%
Since this is a number, I can
put a trace outside of it,

00:21:07.260 --> 00:21:11.670 align:middle line:84%
because the trace of a
number is just a number.

00:21:11.670 --> 00:21:14.110 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:21:14.110 --> 00:21:19.070 align:middle line:84%
And now you remember the trace
have this cyclic properties,

00:21:19.070 --> 00:21:19.570 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:21:19.570 --> 00:21:20.950 align:middle line:90%
Trace have the cyclic property.

00:21:20.950 --> 00:21:24.740 align:middle line:84%
So I can actually move
this to there, OK?

00:21:24.740 --> 00:21:26.660 align:middle line:90%
So I can move it.

00:21:26.660 --> 00:21:31.400 align:middle line:84%
So now I can write it
as e to the 4 s square.

00:21:31.400 --> 00:21:34.000 align:middle line:90%


00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:39.070 align:middle line:84%
I can just move this to there
so that the two come together.

00:21:39.070 --> 00:21:48.320 align:middle line:84%
So we have vr2, v bar
r2, gamma mu, and ur1.

00:21:48.320 --> 00:21:54.200 align:middle line:90%
u bar r1 times trace.

00:21:54.200 --> 00:22:02.060 align:middle line:84%
Similarly, I put this us to
the other side, us1, u bar s1,

00:22:02.060 --> 00:22:04.420 align:middle line:90%
gamma nu.

00:22:04.420 --> 00:22:08.665 align:middle line:90%
Sorry, I missed the gamma nu.

00:22:08.665 --> 00:22:14.900 align:middle line:90%


00:22:14.900 --> 00:22:19.250 align:middle line:84%
Sorry, did I-- so I
put this-- oh, sorry.

00:22:19.250 --> 00:22:20.340 align:middle line:90%
Oh, no.

00:22:20.340 --> 00:22:22.980 align:middle line:90%
Sorry, I just missed that one.

00:22:22.980 --> 00:22:26.710 align:middle line:90%
u bar, r1, gamma nu.

00:22:26.710 --> 00:22:27.870 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:22:27.870 --> 00:22:33.810 align:middle line:84%
And similarly, with that, so
I have u bar s 1 gamma mu.

00:22:33.810 --> 00:22:41.045 align:middle line:84%
And then we have vs2,
v bar s2, and gamma nu.

00:22:41.045 --> 00:22:41.545 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:22:41.545 --> 00:22:46.330 align:middle line:90%


00:22:46.330 --> 00:22:49.090 align:middle line:90%
So I get that.

00:22:49.090 --> 00:22:50.550 align:middle line:90%
So the reason I do that--

00:22:50.550 --> 00:22:53.140 align:middle line:90%


00:22:53.140 --> 00:22:56.170 align:middle line:84%
so now, in this form,
now this is a matrix.

00:22:56.170 --> 00:22:57.760 align:middle line:90%
OK, now this is--

00:22:57.760 --> 00:22:59.680 align:middle line:90%
now this is a column.

00:22:59.680 --> 00:23:01.450 align:middle line:90%
This is a row.

00:23:01.450 --> 00:23:02.745 align:middle line:90%
And this is a matrix.

00:23:02.745 --> 00:23:03.620 align:middle line:90%
And this is a column.

00:23:03.620 --> 00:23:04.370 align:middle line:90%
And this is a row.

00:23:04.370 --> 00:23:07.540 align:middle line:84%
So this is a matrix times
a matrix and times a matrix

00:23:07.540 --> 00:23:09.010 align:middle line:90%
and times a matrix, OK?

00:23:09.010 --> 00:23:12.490 align:middle line:84%
And then you take the trace and
then you get the number, OK--

00:23:12.490 --> 00:23:13.900 align:middle line:84%
similarly with
things since here.

00:23:13.900 --> 00:23:17.560 align:middle line:90%


00:23:17.560 --> 00:23:19.860 align:middle line:84%
And then we need to sum
over all the spins, OK?

00:23:19.860 --> 00:23:21.360 align:middle line:84%
Remember, we need
to actually-- when

00:23:21.360 --> 00:23:23.250 align:middle line:84%
we sum all the
spins, it means we

00:23:23.250 --> 00:23:31.820 align:middle line:84%
sum over all possible with some
order, r2, r1, s1, and s2, OK?

00:23:31.820 --> 00:23:36.290 align:middle line:84%
So now, we can use a
trick which we had when

00:23:36.290 --> 00:23:38.180 align:middle line:90%
we discussed the Dirac spinors.

00:23:38.180 --> 00:23:39.080 align:middle line:90%
OK, so now, recall--

00:23:39.080 --> 00:23:43.630 align:middle line:90%


00:23:43.630 --> 00:23:50.680 align:middle line:84%
now, recall for on-shell
spinors means they both satisfy

00:23:50.680 --> 00:23:52.540 align:middle line:90%
the equation of motion, OK?

00:23:52.540 --> 00:23:57.670 align:middle line:90%
Those all the eigenspinors, OK?

00:23:57.670 --> 00:24:00.730 align:middle line:84%
They satisfy the
following, sum over r--

00:24:00.730 --> 00:24:04.780 align:middle line:84%
if you sum over all
the r of the u, urp--

00:24:04.780 --> 00:24:09.270 align:middle line:90%


00:24:09.270 --> 00:24:19.410 align:middle line:84%
ur bar p-- that give you
i, ip slash plus m, OK?

00:24:19.410 --> 00:24:37.342 align:middle line:84%
And when you sum over v, you get
minus i, minus ik slash plus m.

00:24:37.342 --> 00:24:37.842 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:24:37.842 --> 00:24:41.460 align:middle line:90%


00:24:41.460 --> 00:24:43.890 align:middle line:90%
So now, we see we have--

00:24:43.890 --> 00:24:48.630 align:middle line:84%
if we sum over spin, then
we have these combinations.

00:24:48.630 --> 00:24:51.120 align:middle line:90%
Now, we can use those formulas.

00:24:51.120 --> 00:24:53.780 align:middle line:90%
Now, we can use those formulas.

00:24:53.780 --> 00:25:01.740 align:middle line:84%
So now we find one quarter when
we sum over all the indices,

00:25:01.740 --> 00:25:09.420 align:middle line:90%
r1, r2, s1, s2, the m square--

00:25:09.420 --> 00:25:17.650 align:middle line:90%


00:25:17.650 --> 00:25:23.550 align:middle line:84%
so we get e4 divided
by 4 s squared.

00:25:23.550 --> 00:25:28.250 align:middle line:84%
And then we just apply
those formulas into here.

00:25:28.250 --> 00:25:38.160 align:middle line:84%
OK, so we get trace
minus ip2 slash plus m.

00:25:38.160 --> 00:25:41.100 align:middle line:90%


00:25:41.100 --> 00:25:45.330 align:middle line:84%
So m is the mass of
the initial particle.

00:25:45.330 --> 00:25:49.810 align:middle line:84%
And I take the m prime of the
mass of the final particle.

00:25:49.810 --> 00:25:55.650 align:middle line:84%
So the e plus minus
of mass m and b,

00:25:55.650 --> 00:25:59.550 align:middle line:90%
b bar have mass m prime, OK?

00:25:59.550 --> 00:26:05.500 align:middle line:90%


00:26:05.500 --> 00:26:11.685 align:middle line:84%
So then I have this, then this
times, then this gamma mu.

00:26:11.685 --> 00:26:14.450 align:middle line:90%


00:26:14.450 --> 00:26:16.340 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so this is still
inside this bracket.

00:26:16.340 --> 00:26:20.220 align:middle line:90%


00:26:20.220 --> 00:26:24.135 align:middle line:90%
ip1 slash plus m, gamma nu.

00:26:24.135 --> 00:26:26.810 align:middle line:90%


00:26:26.810 --> 00:26:40.850 align:middle line:84%
And then I have trace ik1
slash plus m prime, gamma mu,

00:26:40.850 --> 00:26:48.980 align:middle line:84%
and then, minus ik2 slash
plus m prime gamma nu.

00:26:48.980 --> 00:26:50.440 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:26:50.440 --> 00:26:53.620 align:middle line:84%
So I just-- when I do
this-- so the spin sum

00:26:53.620 --> 00:26:56.380 align:middle line:84%
is crucial for this
simplification.

00:26:56.380 --> 00:27:01.300 align:middle line:84%
When I sum over spins,
and then without using

00:27:01.300 --> 00:27:07.360 align:middle line:84%
explicit expression of those u
and v, we can write all of them

00:27:07.360 --> 00:27:10.930 align:middle line:84%
just in terms of p slash
and k slash, et cetera.

00:27:10.930 --> 00:27:13.930 align:middle line:90%


00:27:13.930 --> 00:27:16.600 align:middle line:90%
Any questions on this?

00:27:16.600 --> 00:27:20.190 align:middle line:84%
And now we can
evaluate the trace.

00:27:20.190 --> 00:27:22.710 align:middle line:90%
OK, so evaluate the trace.

00:27:22.710 --> 00:27:25.050 align:middle line:84%
Now we need to use
the various formula.

00:27:25.050 --> 00:27:29.280 align:middle line:84%
I think some of them you
have done in your pset.

00:27:29.280 --> 00:27:32.430 align:middle line:90%
Is that now recall.

00:27:32.430 --> 00:27:38.640 align:middle line:84%
So this is the place, all those
exercises, they become useful.

00:27:38.640 --> 00:27:40.910 align:middle line:90%
So become mu.

00:27:40.910 --> 00:27:46.080 align:middle line:84%
So here, if you look at the
structure of these terms--

00:27:46.080 --> 00:27:48.122 align:middle line:90%
so here, there's a p slash.

00:27:48.122 --> 00:27:51.480 align:middle line:84%
So there's one
gamma matrix here.

00:27:51.480 --> 00:27:53.880 align:middle line:84%
And there's another
gamma matrix here.

00:27:53.880 --> 00:27:56.002 align:middle line:84%
